Step 1: Choose a Strong Business Problem

Don’t just say “predict churn”—frame it like a business:

❌ Weak: Predict customer churn
✅ Strong: “Reduce customer churn by 15% by identifying at-risk users early”
Best Dataset Choice:
customer_churn.csv → BEST (recommended)
Real-world relevance
Clear business impact
Alternatives:
sales_data → revenue forecasting
house_prices → price prediction
🧠 Step 2: Define Success Metrics

Think like a company, not a student:

Accuracy is NOT enough
Use:
Precision / Recall
F1-score
ROC-AUC
Business metric: % churn reduced
📊 Step 3: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Go beyond charts—extract insights:

Who is churning most?
Which features matter?
Any surprising patterns?

👉 Example insight:

“Customers with low engagement churn 3x more”

Use:

Seaborn / Matplotlib
Correlation heatmaps
Distribution plots
⚙️ Step 4: Model Development

Don’t just train one model—compare:

Logistic Regression (baseline)
Decision Tree
Random Forest
(Optional) XGBoost

👉 Show:

Feature engineering
Data cleaning
Train-test split
Hyperparameter tuning
🌐 Step 5: Deployment (THIS IS WHAT MAKES YOU STAND OUT)

Most students skip this—don’t.

Option A (Easy):
Use Streamlit
Build a simple app:
Input customer data
Output: “Will churn / Not churn”
Option B (Intermediate):
Use Flask
Create API:
/predict endpoint
🧾 Step 6: Documentation (CRITICAL)

Your project is judged more on explanation than code.

README.md must include:
Problem statement
Dataset description
Approach
Results
Screenshots
How to run
🎤 Step 7: Presentation (10–15 slides)

Structure:

Problem
Business impact
Data overview
Key insights
Model approach
Results
Demo (very important)
Recommendations

👉 Example recommendation:

“Offer discounts to high-risk customers to reduce churn”

💼 Career Preparation (Day 14 Strategy)
🧑‍💻 Build GitHub Portfolio

